B = (-11/2,0);
C = (11/2,0);
M = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(B--D--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
label("$x$", (B + C)/2, S);
label("$1$", (D + M)/2, W);
label("$10$", (A + D)/2, W);
label("$\frac{x}{2}$", (B + M)/2, S);
[/asy]

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $BDC,$
\[\frac{x^2}{4} + \frac{x^2}{4} - 2 \cdot \frac{x}{2} \cdot \frac{x}{2} \cos 3 \angle BAC = 1.\]Then $x^2 (1 - \cos 3 \angle BAC) = 2.$

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABC,$
\[\frac{x^2}{4} + \frac{x^2}{4} - 2 \cdot \frac{x}{2} \cdot \frac{x}{2} \cos \angle BAC = 11^2.\]Then $x^2 (1 - \cos \angle BAC) = 242.$

Hence,
\[\frac{1 - \cos 3 \angle BAC}{1 - \cos \angle BAC} = \frac{2}{242} = \frac{1}{121}.\]From the triple angle formula,
\[\cos 3 \angle BAC = 4 \cos^3 \angle BAC - 3 \cos \angle BAC.\]Then
\[\frac{4 \cos^3 \angle BAC - 3 \cos \angle BAC - 1}{1 - \cos \angle BAC} = \frac{1}{121}.\]This simplifies to $484 \cos^3 \angle BAC - 363 \cos \angle BAC - 122 = 0.$  We can factor this as $(\cos \angle BAC - 1)(484 \cos^2 \angle BAC + 121 \cos \angle BAC + 122) = 0.$  The quadratic factor has no real roots, so $\cos \angle BAC = 1.$  Then $\angle BAC = 0^\circ,$ which is impossible.

Therefore, there is no such triangle $ABC,$ and the perimeter is **undefined**.  Final Answer: $\boxed{\text{undefined}}.$

